entry.title: Automated T* -> raw_ptr<T> rewrite "refresh"
entry.content:
PS1: automated rewrite

PS2-PS5,PS7: unrewrite to fix compilation

PS6,PS22: unrewrite non-automated exclusions

PS8-PS20: apply DanglingUntriaged

PS21: unrewrite to undo binary size increase

PS23: remove no-longer-needed RAW_PTR_EXCLUSION, #includes & comments



The code has changed since the "big rewrite" so some exclusions no

longer apply. But also, the rewriter changed too:

- No longer applies constexpr-related exclusions (raw_ptr<> support

  was added)

- union exclusion has been waived for std::optional and absl::variant,

  since they invoke raw_ptr<>'s ctor/dtor correctly

- Certain paths under //base are no longer need to be excluded, as

PartitionAlloc/raw_ptr no longer depends on them



This CL also tries to popularize a better format of exclusion reasoning

comments, e.g.:

  // RAW_PTR_EXCLUSION: #addr-of, #global-scope

  // RAW_PTR_EXCLUSION: Performance reasons ...

  // RAW_PTR_EXCLUSION: #addr-of; Also: Another reason

One comment per block of fields will suffice, if the reason is the

same throughout, and no other comments are added in between.

This format has advantages, like brevity (no more "not a raw_ptr<>

because" blurb), and improved scriptability.



Bug: 1446392

entry.title: Sort windows from top to bottom for display update
entry.content:
This CL sorts windows from top to bottom when performing a display

configuration update (like display scale change). One reason to do this

is when the windows get larger, if we resize the topmost one first, it

will occlude continue to anything below it while they are also resized

to be larger. We pre-order DFS the window 🌲 from bottom-most to

top-most and collect the windows to avoid quadratic lookup.



In general, there is no best order which optimises non-atomic changes,

but top to bottom is one of the more reasonable ones.



Bug: 1509181

entry.title: Clip occludees to the root window
entry.content:
On display scale change, exo windows are briefly the wrong size due to

async configuration updates. If those windows are maximized and the

display is zoomed in, the exo windows will temporarily be larger than

the root window. Then, if the top window is resized to be smaller, the

below maximized window will become unoccluded in the portion which is

outside the root window and be incorrectly marked as visible. So, this

entry.title: [Android TRM] Add suggestions data classes and image provider.
entry.content:
The Tab Resumption Module on Android will be incorporated into the Magic

Stack, and is a RecyclerView that can undergo frequent destruction and

reconstruction. This CL adds core data structures to enable such usage:

* SuggestionEntry: Modeled on ForeignSessionHelper.ForeignSessionTab

(without direct dependency), the class stores data for a single

suggestion entry (shown as a tile).

* Extra field |sourceName| stores device name.

* Extra field |mUrlDrawable| caches the main image to reduce churn.

* Class is Comparable for ranking. For now, we deem recency as the

main key, followed by various tiebreakers.

the TRM, consisting of a list of SuggestionEntry, and

disk_cache::simple_util::GetEntryHashKey() used a union for type

punning. This is undefined behaviour in C++.

AFAIK the use of reinterpret_cast in this function is still undefined

behaviour, but we couldn't get around that without copying the input,

which would be an unacceptable performance regression.

entry.title: Remove intersection ratio calculation
entry.content:
We were previously calculating the current intersection ratio to

call EnqueueEnteredViewport early (i.e. before we even create an

intersection observer). The calculation however was incorrect;

ratio_visible_area is the ratio of the visible area of the link with

the viewport area, and is not the ratio of the visible area of the

link with the total area of the link (which is what we actually want

to compute here).



Fortunately, the intersection observer created will trigger a call to

EnqueueEnteredViewport shortly after (the current check is done in

DidFinishLifecycleObserver; and the intersection observer would send a

notification in RunPostLifecycleSteps, which runs after the lifecycle

update synchronously), so we could just remove this check. Looking at

the history of this check [1], it was added to avoid making the

intersection observer observe the anchor entirely, but it looks like

we now always observe the anchor regardless of whether it is already

in the viewport or not.



[1] crrev.com/c/2922624

entry.title: android: Make arm64 builds HighEnd by default
entry.content:
The most popular arm64 builds (Trichrome) are shipping with

is_high_end_android. The Monochrome arm64 builds are shipped for old

devices, and we expect these to gradually become less popular.



This change sets is_high_end_android to true for arm64 builds by

default.



This would make local benchmarking slightly less error prone because

there would be a little less to remember to set in GN args when making a

build for the most popular official configuration.



Known effects:



1. Seemingly all official arm64 builders now explicitly set

is_high_end_android. Hence no effect for them.



2. Non-official arm64 builders will change to become high-end, even the

ones that end up running on old devices (example: android-arm64-rel).

In this patch we make sure that is_high_end_android is ignored for

non-official builds (disabled RELR relocations for non-official).

Hence, no effect here as well.



3. Official builds of Monochrome made by devs would fail to run on

Android pre-P (because RELR support is lacking). This leads to

mysterious crashes during something-dlopen in the Android dynamic

linker. Hopefully nobody does this before we remove support for

Android O.

entry.title: Exclude the CT log list from git-secrets hooks.
entry.content:
Some Chromium developers have global git-secrets enforcement on in their

environments, but this detects certificate transparency log list changes

as potential secrets whenever they try to make a commit which includes

them (most often, due to git-merge including it).



This excludes this particular case from that protection, to avoid these

false positives.



The syntax for this file is that every non-blank non-comment line is a

regular expression which is matched against

"filename:linenumber:linecontents" strings, where the filename is

generally but not always relative to the repository root.

entry.title: SyncToSigninMigration: Fix flakiness in EG tests
entry.content:
The tests sometimes failed because there was already data on the

FakeServer at the beginning of the test. This was (apparently) because

the previous test had cleared the FakeServer, but not actually ensured

that those changes get flushed out to disk (which can happen because

the EG framework doesn't always cleanly shut down the app under test).

This CL fixes this by adding explicit "flush to disk" calls after

clearing data.

entry.title: [IdleTimeout] Part 1 of EG Tests for IdleTimeout and IdleTimeoutActions
entry.content:
This is the first part of the tests for IdleTimeout policies egtests.

This mainly tests the cases for showing the dialog and the snackbar.

More tests will be written to test specific actions.



The cases tested and their expectations are as follows:



- `Continue using Chrome` button clicked: no actions run, the snackbar is now shown and the dialog is not dismissed

- The dialog counts down 30 seconds without user interaction: dialog is dismissed, actions run and the snackbar is shown.

- The dialog is shown then the app is backgrounded: on re-foreground, the actions run and the dialog is not shown. The snackbar shows after actions run.

- Multiple windows: The dialog shows in one of the windows

- Multiple windows and the window showing the dialog is closed: the dialog should transfer to the other window still opened.



The CL also fixes and improves a few bugs that affects some tests and improve consistency of the variables that the service has access to.

entry.title: [mullet] Update metrics to handle new M3 use cases.
entry.content:
Why?



Turns out M3 for passwords is also going to have full form filling

(This was not initially true). This means the regular popup

for passwords will be updated to also have children suggestion,

not only when triggering from the context menu.



Therefore we will want to measure whether users will use full filling

or field by field filling also for passwords.

This metric is measured by the FillingMethodUsed,

which before was making no differentiation between filling products.

Since the assumption was that only addresses would have non

field-by-field filling.



To go ahead and for completion I am also starting to log

FillingMethodUsed for unclassified fields

(which can only be field by field filling) and log field-by-field

filling for unclassified fields as well. With this, it will be easier

to just add new buckets in the future.



Metrics:



*MethodUsed.Address.TriggeringFieldDoesNotMatchFillingProduct

*MethodUsed.Address.TriggeringFieldMatchesFillingProduct

*MethodUsed.CreditCard.TriggeringFieldDoesNotMatchFillingProduct

*MethodUsed.CreditCard.TriggeringFieldMatchesFillingProduct

*FieldTypeUsed.Address.TriggeringFieldDoesNotMatchFillingProduct

*FieldTypeUsed.Address.TriggeringFieldMatchesFillingProduct

*FieldTypeUsed.CreditCard.TriggeringFieldDoesNotMatchFillingProduct

*FieldTypeUsed.CreditCard.TriggeringFieldMatchesFillingProduct



One caveat about these metrics is that TriggeringFieldDoesNotMatchFillingProduct

bucket can only happen on field by field filling

(the other filling methods require field classification).



Note: The feature is not rolled out, therefore we do not have to

worry about losing metrics.



DEMO: https://screencast.googleplex.com/cast/NTYwMzAxNzU0MDc2MzY0OHw3NGUzMDA3Ny1mOQ



OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAMS=Moved to a more more fine grained granularity to

account for new use cases.
